# Safe Development

## Core Security Rules

- Never commit secrets (plaintext or base64 placeholders with real values).
- Validate external input and fail safely.
- Do not leak secrets in logs, errors, or debug output.
- Handle file paths securely (avoid path traversal vulnerabilities).

## Windows-Specific Security

- **Administrator privileges** — zapret2 requires admin rights for WinDivert. Document this clearly.
- **UAC prompts** — ensure users understand why admin rights are needed.
- **File system access** — validate all file paths before reading/writing.
- **Process execution** — sanitize all arguments passed to subprocess calls.

## Secret Management

- **No secrets in code** — use environment variables or secure configuration files.
- **Jenkins Credentials** — store API keys and tokens in Jenkins Credentials Store.
- **GitHub Secrets** — use GitHub repository secrets for Actions workflows.
- If a secret was ever committed, rotate immediately and document rotation.

## CI/CD Safety

- CI should include secret scanning (gitleaks or similar).
- Test builds should not expose sensitive data in logs.
- Artifact publishing requires authentication (API keys).

## Runtime Hardening

- Validate all user inputs (preset names, file paths, domain lists).
- Handle errors gracefully without exposing internal details.
- Log security-relevant events (failed auth, invalid inputs).
- Keep dependencies updated (requirements.txt).

## Code Review Checklist

- [ ] No hardcoded secrets or credentials
- [ ] Input validation for all external data
- [ ] Error handling doesn't leak sensitive info
- [ ] File operations use safe paths
- [ ] Subprocess calls sanitize arguments
- [ ] Admin privilege requirements documented

